				<outline text="Major Bay Area highway outage" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 05:04:45 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="This morning there's a report on local news that a critical piece of Bay Area roadway is out, and may be out for weeks or months." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 14:51:32 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The biggest traffic bottleneck in a traffic-challenged metropolitan area is known as the &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MacArthur_Maze&quot;&gt;MacArthur Maze&lt;/a&gt;. Four major freeways, 880, 580, 24 and 80 all come together from the East Bay, and from the other side -- the Bay Bridge connects all that with San Francisco." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 14:52:14 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Early this morning a gasoline tanker truck caught fire on a ramp connecting 580 westbound with 880, causing 250 yards of freeway to collapse. " created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 14:54:22 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;http://maps.google.com/?ie=UTF8&amp;z=15&amp;ll=37.82743,-122.292659&amp;spn=0.022169,0.036693&amp;t=h&amp;om=1&quot;&gt;Google map&lt;/a&gt; of the maze. " created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:05:11 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Reports from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/baycitynews/archive/2007/04/29/fire29.DTL&quot;&gt;SF Chron&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://abclocal.go.com/kgo/story?section=local&amp;id=5255706&quot;&gt;KGO&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mercurynews.com/breakingnews/ci_5780113&quot;&gt;Mercury News&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.contracostatimes.com/ci_5780122&quot;&gt;Contra Costa Times&lt;/a&gt;." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 14:58:17 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="New Twitter support in OPML Editor" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:12:24 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="Yesterday I released new code that allows you to browse the posts from all the people you're following on Twitter." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:12:47 GMT"/>
					<outline text="How to: 1. Choose Update opml.root from the File menu. 2. Click on OK. 3. Quit and relaunch the OPML Editor app." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:40:01 GMT"/>
					<outline text="There's a new &lt;a href=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/04/29/twitterSubmenu.gif&quot;&gt;Twitter sub-menu&lt;/a&gt; of the Community menu, with two commands: 1. The Preferences command allows you to set your Twitter username and password, and 2. My Twitter Friends opens an outline &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.scripting.com/stories/2007/04/28/myTwitterFriends.html&quot;&gt;window&lt;/a&gt; with a list of your friends. " created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:40:31 GMT"/>
					<outline text="In the window, when you double-click on a friend's name, after a short delay, we &lt;a href=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/04/29/expandedfriendnolinks.gif&quot;&gt;display&lt;/a&gt; the last 20 status messages posted by that person. If the the message contained a URL, the outline node is a link, if you double-click it, the link opens in your web browser (&lt;a href=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/04/29/friendWithLinks.gif&quot;&gt;screen shot&lt;/a&gt;). Although I haven't tried it yet, if the URL ends with .opml, it should open in-place, since that's a hack the OPML Editor uses to trigger an OPML inclusion. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:41:55 GMT"/>
					<outline text="As usual, report any problems &lt;a href=&quot;http://scripting.wordpress.com/2007/04/29/scripting-news-for-4292007/#comments&quot;&gt;here&lt;/a&gt;, or on one of the mail lists." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:44:56 GMT"/>
					<outline text="PS: &lt;a href=&quot;http://blogs.opml.org/amyloo/2007/04/29#nowIGetIt&quot;&gt;Amyloo got it&lt;/a&gt; before I even wrote it up. &quot;;-&gt;&quot;" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 15:53:59 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="April 28" created="Sat, 28 Apr 2007 05:00:01 GMT">
				<outline text="Spreadsheet calls over the Internet?" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:38:24 GMT" name="spreadsheetCallsOverTheInternet" type="outline">
					<outline text="&lt;img src=&quot;http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2007/04/28/coffee.jpg&quot; width=&quot;95&quot; height=&quot;156&quot; border=&quot;0&quot; align=&quot;right&quot; hspace=&quot;15&quot; vspace=&quot;5&quot; alt=&quot;A picture named coffee.jpg&quot;&gt;I like having a spreadsheet around, but until Google came out with their browser-based &lt;a href=&quot;http://spreadsheets.google.com&quot;&gt;spreadsheet&lt;/a&gt;, I hadn't used one in many years. I find Office too much software, and all the other spreadsheets I had learned either didn't run on my machine or weren't being actively maintained. Without thinking much I had stopped using them." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:38:35 GMT"/>
					<outline text="But now I use it for all kinds of little tasks that require an array of values, or a bit of calculation. Now I'd like to start building more of my life around a spreadsheet, to use it to monitor various processes on my servers, but to do this, there will have to be a protocol for plugging web apps into the spreadsheet." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:40:29 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Here's the syntax I imagine using:" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:42:55 GMT"/>
					<outline text="&lt;code&gt;[server].getPortfolioValue (username, password)&lt;/code&gt;" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:43:01 GMT"/>
					<outline text="It would work just like a built-in spreadsheet function except the call would go out over the net, run the procedure on the indicated server, and display the value it returns, formatted according to how the spreadsheet author says it should be formatted." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:46:13 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The server url would include a protocol, server name, port and path. I would recommend doing &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.xmlrpc.com/&quot;&gt;XML-RPC&lt;/a&gt; first, it's the simplest, most uniformly implemented RPC out there. You'd have to do some form of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.soapware.org/&quot;&gt;SOAP&lt;/a&gt;, and extend REST with standards for serializing and de-serializing parameter lists and returned values (or you could adopt the serialization format from one of the other protocols). " created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:49:42 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Example: &lt;code&gt;xmlrpc:\//rpc.fidelity.com:7092/&lt;/code&gt;" created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:53:22 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Interestingly, this is one of the demos Microsoft did for &lt;a href=&quot;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiplan&quot;&gt;Multiplan&lt;/a&gt; for the IBM-PC in the early 80s when it was competing with Visicalc. Then, it was a good vision, but impractical. Today it's practical and would be very useful and would lead to many interesting apps, perhaps even businesses." created="Sun, 29 Apr 2007 00:47:59 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				<outline text="Today's links" created="Sat, 28 Apr 2007 23:18:58 GMT" type="outline">
					<outline text="&quot;So what?&quot; is &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.onebyonemedia.com/the-blogosphere-has-stalled-at-155-million-blogs-so-what/&quot;&gt;exactly right&lt;/a&gt;. Imagine saying that the number of telephone calls had stalled at 15.6 million. Or the number of Word docs. Blogs aren't businesses, they're documents, or at best collections of documents. Counting them is an meaningless exercise. Look for individuals who are changing things &lt;i&gt;using&lt;/i&gt; blogs, that's what's important." created="Sat, 28 Apr 2007 23:31:19 GMT"/>
